          "Performance Metric: Best Model",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Intelligent Tutoring Systems",
          "Next Question Correctedness",
          "Correct (1) vs Incorrect (0)",
          "3852 learners in ASSISTments2009, 27485 learners in ASSISTments2012, 5000 EdNet learners",
          "Each dataset refers to its own context",
          "Sequences of Answers, Knowledge Concepts",
          "[Question Embeddings, Concept Embeddings, Difficulty Embeddings]",
          "When it comes to Graph models for KT, GKT does not select the most suitable graphs to be used for a KT model whilst others do not establish relationships between questions and knowledge concepts. \n\nMoreoverr, other models (CoKT) use far too simplistic measures of similarity,",
          "The authors introduce Feature Crosses - essencially the creation of non-linear higher-order featurescreated by combining 2 or more features of the original feature space. \n\n",
          "The authors create an Multi-Relational Heterogenous Graph establishing relationships between learners, questions and concepts. \n\nDifficulty of questions is defined from the ratio between incorrect responses and total responses to a question.\n\nThe original embeddings are converted into a different set of embeddings from the product between the original forms of embeddings at the feature cross module - mapping the feature space into a Hilberrt space. \n\nFrom the Feature Cross Module, the authors feed it into the Knowledge State Evolution Module where the knowledge state of the student is created and updated before going into the prediction.\n\nEmbedding size was set to 100.",
          "BKT, KTM, DKVMN, DKT, DKT+, GIKT, GAKT, CoKT, FCIKT ",
          "Holdout Method",
          "AST09\n{AUC: 0.7912 - FCIKT}\n\nAST12\n{AUC: 0.802 - FCIKT}\n\nEdNet\n{AUC: 0.7463 - FCIKT}",
          "Authors propose a new model that includes Feature Crosses to change the feature space before using that space as input for the knowledge state estimation.\n\nThe model outperforms all baselines. Moreoverr, the authors introduce an Ablation Study that evaluates the performance of the KT model while testing the removal of different elements: results show that all elements are important for prediction, with the feature crosses being more important than multihead attention.\n\nAdditionally, the authors also did a sensitivity analysis, a case study, and a visual analysis of the latent concepts. ",
          "- Holdout Method"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 9
    }
